Goal

Leg 1's job is to catch application errors as they happen, gather enough context around each one, and hand off a clean, structured package that Leg 2 can feed directly into Amazon Bedrock for root-cause analysis. Leg 1 does not do any AI reasoning itself — it's purely detection, cleanup, and packaging.

What was built

1. CloudWatch log source

Identified /PayActiv/internalapis/code as the log group to monitor, out of ~791 total log groups in the account, since it's where backend/API errors for the internal APIs surface.

2. CloudWatch Subscription Filter

A filter pattern was defined to only trigger on log lines that actually matter:

?ERROR ?Exception ?Failed ?Timeout ?500 ?NullReferenceException ?StackTrace

This means the Lambda function below only runs when something resembling a real error appears — not on every log line — which keeps invocation counts (and downstream Bedrock costs) low.

3. Lambda function (log_processor)

Written in Python. On each trigger, it:


Decodes the gzip/base64 CloudWatch payload
Extracts the error message, log group, log stream, and timestamp
Fetches the surrounding log lines (±30 seconds) around the error using logs.get_log_events, so there's real context for analysis later, not just a bare error string
Filters out known noise (health checks, pings, warmups, debug/info lines) so those never even make it to storage


4. Snowflake config check

Added a module (snowflake_config.py) that checks whether a given error/application pair should be ignored, and what severity (High/Medium/Low) and routing team it maps to.

Status: stubbed, not yet live. Snowflake isn't connected with real credentials yet, so this currently runs on local keyword-based defaults (e.g. timeouts → High severity → infra team). The real Snowflake query is already written in the file's docstring — once credentials exist, only that one function needs to be filled in; nothing else in the pipeline changes.

5. Bedrock payload preparation

Added a module (bedrock_payload.py) that takes the cleaned error + context + severity/routing and assembles it into the exact structured object Leg 2 will hand to Bedrock — including a pre-written prompt asking for root cause, quick fix, long-term fix, and relevant C#/SQL snippets.

6. Storage

Two DynamoDB tables:


ProActiv-ErrorContext — the raw cleaned record (error, context logs, severity, routing)
ProActiv-BedrockPayloads — the final structured payload, ready for Leg 2 to read and send straight to Bedrock with no extra assembly required


